To provision an egress-only internet gateway for IPv6-compatible instances within a given VPC on AWS, we'll follow these steps:

1. Define the provider, in this case, AWS.
2. Define the specific VPC where the egress-only internet gateway will be attached.
3. Define the egress-only internet gateway resource, set its name as "pike", and attach it to the given VPC.
4. Apply a tag `permissions` to the egress-only internet gateway.

Below is the Terraform configuration in HCL format:

```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-west-2" # Example region; adjust as needed
}

resource "aws_vpc" "example" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16" # Example VPC CIDR block; adjust as needed

  # Example tags
  tags = {
    Name = "example-vpc"
  }
}

resource "aws_egress_only_internet_gateway" "pike" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.example.id

  # Example tags
  tags = {
    Name = "pike"
    permissions = "restricted-outbound"
  }
}
```

Make sure to replace the `region`, and any example settings like `cidr_block` with your specific environment details. This configuration sets up an egress-only internet gateway, applies the specified tag, and associates it with the specified VPC.

